00:00:19.313 --> 00:00:20.818
And now they want us to
evaluate the derivative

00:00:20.818 --> 00:00:25.270
with respect to x of the
product of f of x and h of x

00:00:25.270 --> 00:00:27.165
when x is equal to three.

00:00:27.165 --> 00:00:28.818
One way you could view this is,

00:00:28.818 --> 00:00:31.459
if we viewed some function,

00:00:31.459 --> 00:00:34.308
if we viewed some function g of x.

00:00:34.308 --> 00:00:38.439
g of x as being equal
to the product of f of x

00:00:38.439 --> 00:00:39.356
and h of x,

00:00:40.685 --> 00:00:42.945
this expression is the
derivative of g of x.

00:00:42.945 --> 00:00:47.112
So we could write g prime of
x is equal to the derivative

00:00:48.057 --> 00:00:50.060
with respect to x

00:00:50.060 --> 00:00:50.893
of f of x

00:00:52.318 --> 00:00:53.401
times h of x.

00:00:55.487 --> 00:00:56.989
Which is what we see right here,

00:00:56.989 --> 00:00:59.480
and which is what we want to
evaluate at x equals three.

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:00.763
So we essentially want to evaluate

00:01:00.763 --> 00:01:01.596
g prime

00:01:02.761 --> 00:01:04.102
of three.

00:01:04.102 --> 00:01:06.320
This is what they're asking us to do.

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:08.949
Well, to do that, let's go first up here.

00:01:08.949 --> 00:01:09.956
Let's just think about what this is doing.

00:01:09.956 --> 00:01:11.153
They're asking us to take the derivative

00:01:11.153 --> 00:01:13.436
with respect to x of the
product of two functions

00:01:13.436 --> 00:01:15.444
that we have some information about.

00:01:15.444 --> 00:01:17.320
Well, if we're taking the
derivative of the product

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:18.691
of two functions, you
could imagine that the

00:01:18.691 --> 00:01:21.376
